<h1><a href="/diseases-conditions/amyotrophic-lateral-sclerosis/symptoms-causes/syc-20354022">Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS)</a></h1>



</div>
<div class="row"><div class="requestappointment"><a ID="et_linkAppointment_titlebar" href="/appointments" class="ico-appt"><span></span>Request an Appointment</a></div></div>
<nav class="mobile-nav-container" aria-label="Secondary"><div class="row"><div id="access-nav"><ul role="menubar"><li role="menuitem"><a href="/diseases-conditions/amyotrophic-lateral-sclerosis/symptoms-causes/syc-20354022" id="et_genericNavigation_symptoms-causes" class="on" aria-current="true">Symptoms &<br />causes</a></li><li role="menuitem"><a href="/diseases-conditions/amyotrophic-lateral-sclerosis/diagnosis-treatment/drc-20354027" id="et_genericNavigation_diagnosis-treatment">Diagnosis &<br />treatment</a></li><li role="menuitem"><a href="/diseases-conditions/amyotrophic-lateral-sclerosis/doctors-departments/ddc-20354029" id="et_genericNavigation_doctors-departments">Doctors &<br />departments</a></li><li role="menuitem"><a href="/diseases-conditions/amyotrophic-lateral-sclerosis/care-at-mayo-clinic/mac-20354030" id="et_genericNavigation_care-at-mayo-clinic">Care at<br />Mayo Clinic</a></li></ul></div></div></nav>

<!--googleon: all-->
<article id="main-content">
<div class="row">
<div class="content">
<div id="phmaincontent_0_ctl01_divByLine" class="thin-content-bar">
<div class="print"><a href="/diseases-conditions/amyotrophic-lateral-sclerosis/symptoms-causes/syc-20354022?p=1" >Print</a></div>
</div>



<div>
<!--googleoff: all--><h2>Overview</h2><!--googleon: all--><p>Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (a-my-o-TROE-fik LAT-ur-ul skluh-ROE-sis), known as ALS, is a nervous system disease that affects nerve cells in the brain and spinal cord. <abbr title="Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr> causes loss of muscle control. The disease gets worse over time.</p><div data-nosnippet="true"><div id="ad-mobile-top-container"></div></div>
<p><abbr title="Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr> is often called Lou Gehrig's disease after the baseball player who was diagnosed with it. The exact cause of the disease is still not known. A small number of cases are inherited.</p>
<p><abbr title="Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr> often begins with muscle twitching and weakness in an arm or leg, trouble swallowing or slurred speech. Eventually <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr> affects control of the muscles needed to move, speak, eat and breathe. There is no cure for this fatal disease.</p><!--googleoff: all--><div id="maincta" class="acces-list-container rc-list"><h3>Products & Services</h3><div class="list-wrapper"><ul id="ul_e6d09fbd-19fe-49ac-9b47-bd857c0d411b" class="listGroup"><li class="acces-listitems"><a href="https://order.store.mayoclinic.com/flex/mmv/fhblc01/?altkey=FHBORG&utm_source=MC-DotOrg-PS&utm_medium=Link&utm_campaign=FamilyHealth-Book&utm_content=FHB">A Book: Mayo Clinic Family Health Book</a></li><li class="acces-hide-listitems"><a href="https://order.store.mayoclinic.com/flex/mmv/hldigar/?altkey=HLEMORG">Newsletter: Mayo Clinic Health Letter &mdash; Digital Edition</a></li></ul><button id="btn_e6d09fbd-19fe-49ac-9b47-bd857c0d411b" class="acces-list-show-hide" type="button" data-ending="false" data-show="Show more products from Mayo Clinic" data-hide="Show fewer products from Mayo Clinic" data-show-count="0" aria-controls="ul_e6d09fbd-19fe-49ac-9b47-bd857c0d411b">Show more products from Mayo Clinic</button></div></div><!--googleon: all-->
<div id="redpoint_emailform_1"></div>

<div>
<div>
</div>

</div>

<h2>Symptoms</h2><p>Symptoms of <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr> vary from person to person. Symptoms depend on which nerve cells are affected. <abbr title="Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr> generally begins with muscle weakness that spreads and gets worse over time. Symptoms might include:</p>
<ul>
<li>Trouble walking or doing usual daily activities.</li>
<li>Tripping and falling.</li>
<li>Weakness in the legs, feet or ankles.</li>
<li>Hand weakness or clumsiness.</li>
<li>Slurred speech or trouble swallowing.</li>
<li>Weakness associated with muscle cramps and twitching in the arms, shoulders and tongue.</li>
<li>Untimely crying, laughing or yawning.</li>
<li>Thinking or behavioral changes.</li>
</ul>
<p><abbr title="Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr> often starts in the hands, feet, arms or legs. Then it spreads to other parts of the body. Muscles get weaker as more nerve cells die. This eventually affects chewing, swallowing, speaking and breathing.</p>
<p>There's generally no pain in the early stages of <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr>. Pain also is not common in the later stages. <abbr title="Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr> doesn't usually affect bladder control. It also usually doesn't affect the senses, including the ability to taste, smell, touch and hear.</p>

<h2>Causes</h2><p><abbr title="Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr> affects the nerve cells that control voluntary muscle movements such as walking and talking. These nerve cells are called motor neurons. There are two groups of motor neurons. The first group extends from the brain to the spinal cord to muscles throughout the body. They're referred to as upper motor neurons. The second group extends from the spinal cord to muscles throughout the body. They're referred to as lower motor neurons.</p>
<p><abbr title="Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr> causes both groups of motor neurons to gradually deteriorate and then die. When motor neurons are damaged, they stop sending messages to the muscles. As a result, the muscles can't function.</p>
<p>For about 10% of people with <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr>, a genetic cause can be identified. For the rest, the cause is not known.</p>
<p>Researchers continue to study possible causes of <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr>. Most theories center on a complex interaction between genes and factors in the environment.</p>
<h2>Risk factors</h2><p>Established risk factors for <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr> include:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Genetics.</strong> For about 10% of people with <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr>, a risk gene was passed down from a family member. This is called hereditary <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr>. In most people with hereditary <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr>, their children have a 50% chance of inheriting the gene.</li>
<li><strong>Age.</strong> Risk increases with age up to age 75. <abbr title="Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr> is most common between the ages of 60 and the mid-80s.</li>
<li><strong>Sex.</strong> Before the age of 65, slightly more men than women develop <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr>. This sex difference disappears after age 70.</li>
</ul>
<p>Environmental factors, such as the following, have been associated with an increased risk of <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr>.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Smoking.</strong> Evidence supports that smoking is an environmental risk factor for <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr>. Women who smoke seem to be at even higher risk, particularly after menopause.</li>
<li><strong>Environmental toxin exposure.</strong> Some evidence suggests that exposure to lead or other substances in the workplace or at home might be linked to <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr>. Much study has been done, but no one agent or chemical has been consistently associated with <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr>.</li>
<li><strong>Military service.</strong> Studies indicate that people who have served in the military are at higher risk of <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr>. It's not clear what about military service might trigger <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr>. It might include exposure to certain metals or chemicals, traumatic injuries, viral infections, or intense exertion.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Complications</h2><p>As the disease progresses, <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr> causes complications, such as:</p>
<h3>Breathing problems</h3><p>Over time, <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr> leads to weakness of the muscles used to breathe. People with <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr> might need a device such as a mask ventilator to help them breathe at night. The device is similar to what someone with sleep apnea might wear. This type of device supports the person's breathing through a mask worn over the nose, the mouth or both.</p>
<p>Some people with advanced <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr> choose to have a tracheostomy. This is a surgically created hole at the front of the neck leading to the windpipe. A ventilator may work better on a tracheostomy than on a mask.</p>
<p>The most common cause of death for people with <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr> is breathing failure. Half of people with <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr> die within 14 to 18 months of diagnosis. However, some people with <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr> live 10 years or longer.</p>
<h3>Speaking problems</h3><p>Most people with <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr> develop weakness of the muscles used to form speech. This usually starts with slower speech and occasional slurring of words. It then becomes harder to speak clearly. This can progress to the point that others can't understand the person's speech. Other forms of communication and technology are used to communicate.</p>
<h3>Eating problems</h3><p>People with <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr> can develop weakness of the muscles involved with swallowing. This can lead to malnutrition and dehydration. They are also at higher risk of getting food, liquids or saliva into the lungs, which can cause pneumonia. A feeding tube can reduce these risks and ensure proper hydration and nutrition.</p>
<h3>Dementia</h3><p>Some people with <abbr title="amyotrophic lateral sclerosis">ALS</abbr> have problems with language and decision-making. Some are eventually diagnosed with a form of dementia called frontotemporal dementia.</p>
<h2></h2>
<p>

</p>

<script type="text/javascript">
(function () {
if (document.querySelector('body').classList.contains('gsr') && document.body.clientWidth > 752 && document.body.clientWidth < 905) {
var topAd = document.querySelector("#gpt-ad-mayoclinic\\.org-top");
var bottomAd = document.querySelector("#gpt-ad-mayoclinic\\.org-bottom");

if (topAd !== null) {
moveTopAd(topAd);
}

if (bottomAd !== null) {
moveBottomAd(bottomAd);
}
}

function moveTopAd(topAd) {
var adMobileTopContainer = document.getElementById("ad-mobile-top-container");

if (adMobileTopContainer !== null) {
adMobileTopContainer.classList.add("mayoad");

adMobileTopContainer.innerHTML = "<span class=\"heading\">Advertisement</span>";
adMobileTopContainer.appendChild(topAd);

adMobileTopContainer.appendChild(document.querySelector(".policy"));
}
}

function moveBottomAd(bottomAd) {
var adMobileWrapper = document.createElement("div");
adMobileWrapper.setAttribute("data-nosnippet", "true");

var adMobileBottomContainer = document.createElement("div");

adMobileBottomContainer.setAttribute("id", "ad-mobile-bottom-container");
adMobileBottomContainer.classList.add("mayoad");

var adMobileBottomDestination = document.querySelector("span.moddate");

if (adMobileBottomDestination === null) {
adMobileBottomDestination = document.querySelector("div.pubdate");
}

if (adMobileBottomDestination === null) {
adMobileBottomDestination = document.querySelector("menu.social");
}

if (adMobileBottomDestination !== null) {
adMobileBottomDestination.insertAdjacentElement("afterend", adMobileWrapper);

adMobileBottomContainer.innerHTML = "<span class=\"heading\">Advertisement</span>";
adMobileBottomContainer.appendChild(bottomAd);

var adPolicy = document.querySelector(".policy").cloneNode(true);
adMobileBottomContainer.appendChild(adPolicy);

adMobileWrapper.appendChild(adMobileBottomContainer)
}
}
})();
</script>
